# Vertical slices & JUCE-first

Read [PROJECT-SPEC.md](../../PROJECT-SPEC.md) §2.5–2.7, §14, §17 before implementing a user story.

## Do not reinvent the wheel

- **JSON (C++):** use `juce::JSON` / `juce::var` / `juce::DynamicObject` for project and config serialization. Do **not** add hand-rolled string parsers for JSON.
- **JUCE elsewhere:** prefer JUCE modules already in the dependency tree (`juce_core`, audio, etc.) before custom utilities.
- **OS I/O:** use platform save/open dialogs (Android SAF `CreateDocument` / `OpenDocument`, etc.) — not folder-tree pickers or raw path text fields for user-facing save/load.
- **Realtime path:** still no JSON parsing on the audio thread (parse on control thread, then apply snapshot).

## Ship the full slice — “wow moment”

A vertical slice is **done** when a PO can demo it once on device without follow-up amendments:

- End-to-end UX (button → native dialog → engine → UI refresh)
- Clear success, cancel, and error feedback
- Round-trip or playback proof where persistence/audio is involved
- C++ tests that exercise **real** serialized output (not mocks only)

If acceptance criteria omit dialogs, error states, or the demo script, **expand the ticket first**, then implement.

**Companion tickets:** every user-facing `US-XX-YY` needs `US-XX-YY-ux-ui.md` and `US-XX-YY-interaction.md` (PROJECT-SPEC.md §14.1). The `feature-contract-architect` subagent generates the architecture contract first; then the `layout-contract-designer` subagent produces `docs/features/<name>/09-ux-flow-contract.md` before implementation begins.

**Investor bar (§2.8):** Bold, complete slices; no overengineering; verify on device; mobile UX matters.
